<subSubSection box="[151,395,1086,1113]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,395,1086,1113]" box="[151,395,1086,1113]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,395,1086,1113]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,395,1086,1113]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[207,313,1086,1113]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saturella">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[207,313,1086,1113]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">saturella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1159,1509]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
Externally, species are characterized by the dark brown fascia of the forewing (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1146,1159,1185]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); creamish white or yellowish cream to ochreous yellow frontal tuft. In the male genitalia, the uncus is comprised of two short, rounded lateral lobes; the gnathos is uniquely-shaped, pointed apically and with a slender, hook-like projection basally; the vinculum is without a juxta, and heavily folded medially (
<figureCitation box="[803,868,1267,1293]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). In the female genitalia, apophyses are long; anal papillae are unique, modified into a single, wide, short transverse lobe with a distinctive, trianglular process (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1904,1928]" captionTargetBox="[177,1411,192,1870]" captionTargetId="figure-18@4.[169,1417,181,1880]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Pictorial diagnostic tool for identification of Oriental Pseudopostega species groups (Note: the morphological structures are drawn in different scales). * – except for P. similantis with an indistinctive dorsal spot; ** – formerly the nigrimaculella group; *** – Mediterranean P. matrona sp. nov., described below" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4554948" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4554948/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); signum is strongly developed (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[535,623,1339,1364]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="javae">
<emphasis box="[535,623,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">P. javae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[677,847,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphivittata">
<emphasis box="[677,847,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">P. amphivittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or weakly developed (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[1112,1239,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saturella">
<emphasis box="[1112,1239,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">P. saturella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1159,1509]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
From other groups of the Oriental (or Neotropical) 
<taxonomicName box="[778,948,1375,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[778,948,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Pseudopostega</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Puplesis &amp; Robinson" authorityYear="1999" box="[1004,1103,1375,1401]" class="Insecta" family="Opostegidae" genus="Pseudopostega" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saturella">
<emphasis box="[1004,1103,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">saturella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group is distinguished by the unique shape of the gnathos in the male genitalia and anal papillae with a distinctive, triangular process in the female genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1332,1483,1509]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1159,1509]" box="[199,1332,1483,1509]" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">
Distribution. Currently the group is comprised of three species distributed in 
<collectingCountry box="[1062,1162,1483,1509]" name="Thailand" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1216,1329,1483,1509]" name="Indonesia" pageId="5" pageNumber="346">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
